        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cd28b8e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>3:6.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Limitations on Panel&apos;s power</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s power is national in reach and it can have a significant <?pagebreak label="28"?>impact on cases
                        throughout the country.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Nonetheless, it has a limited role that attorneys often fail to grasp: it exists to decide
                        whether multiple cases with common fact issues pending in the federal courts should be
                        transferred for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It also decides when remand of transferred cases is appropriate.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Although it might be wise or efficient for the Panel to have additional powers, it does
                        not.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Class Action Fairness Act contains one limitation on the Panel&apos;s power to
                        transfer.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In allows removal of actions to federal court from state court where, among other things,
                        they qualify as “mass actions.”[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I026aace0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] The
                        statute also prohibits transfer of removed mass actions by the Panel.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I026aace1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">2</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has interpreted this provision as prohibiting transfer only of actions where the mass-action
                        provision is the only basis for removal (in many cases multiple grounds for removal may exist.)[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I026aace2680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has declined to transfer removed cases until the basis upon which federal jurisdiction is based
                        has been determined by the district to which the actions were removed.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I026aace3680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
